# Chapter 2 — To the Gates of the Sun (Tun-huang, China)

*Keeper-facing summary of Chapter 2 of The Children of Fear. Structure lives in
the sibling `.arc`, stat blocks in the `.actor`, and the campaign's central lore
in `children-of-fear-0.4-campaign-overview.lore`. Consult your copy of the
campaign for the full text, read-aloud passages, and handouts.*

## Role in the campaign

Chapter 2 carries the party west from Sian to the Caves of the Thousand Buddhas
at Tun-huang, where the mundane errand (reach Warner, secure the secret cave)
gives way to the campaign's true premise. Here the investigators meet the
strange ***lama*** who reveals the stakes — Shambhala, Agartha, and the King of
Fear — and sets the gathering quest that drives Chapters 3–5. It is the hinge
between the recruitment and the any-order middle.

## Part One — Chang'an (Sian)

**Start — A Damp Reception.** The convoy from Peking reaches Sian's walls under
penetrating drizzle; gate soldiers spot-check papers of those *entering* (Wang's
permit eases this). The **Tokabhaya** keep working on the party — the *Visions in
the Dark* continue as dreams by night (regional handout: *What Your Investigator
Knows — Sian and the Kansu Corridor*).

**The Monastery of Flourishing Teaching.** At the ancient Hsing-Chiao Temple
stands **Hiuen-Tsiang's** five-tiered funerary pagoda; investigators can read the
monk's own account of gathering his manuscripts — background on the 7th-century
pilgrim whose route and legacy anchor the campaign (handout on Hiuen-Tsiang).

**Set Up — Hiring and Firing.** From Sian onward the party must assemble their
own caravan — porters, pack animals, carts. Their key contact is **Mi Han**, the
caravan-master Wang recommended; hiring (and vetting) the expedition is the
chapter's logistical spine.

**An Uncivil War.** A subplot of displaced **White Russian** refugees and defeated
White Army remnants (echoes of the 1917 revolutions and the Russian Civil War)
colours the road and can entangle the investigators.

**On the road west.** The expedition travels the Ho-hsi / Kansu (Hexi/Gansu)
Corridor toward the oasis of Tun-huang, with provided *en-route* encounters (the
Travel-by-Map device) building strangeness along the way.

## Part Two — The Blazing Beacon (Tun-huang)

**Set Up — Hidden Treasures.** Background on the Caves of the Thousand Buddhas
(Ch'ien-fo-tung) and the notorious **Library Cave**: for two decades Western
archaeologists — chief among them **Sir Marc Aurel Stein** — bought and carried
off its manuscripts from the caretaker priest **Wang Yuanlu**, feeding the
Chinese resentment the campaign keeps foregrounding.

**Start — A Warm Welcome.** At the caves the party finally meets **Langdon
Warner** — a large, red-headed, fedora-wearing American — whose telegram (handout:
*Decaying Splendor 3*) brought them here, and the matter of the rumored secret,
resealed cave.

**The lama and the true quest.** Here the campaign turns: the *lama* gives the
investigators his own version of the **Buddhist history of Shambhala** (handout:
*Gates 3*) — the central lore of the twin kingdoms, the King of Fear, and the
opening Gates of Agartha — and enlists them to help avert catastrophe by
gathering what a ritual to bind the King of Fear requires. Asked where to begin,
he offers route advice (handout: *Gates 5*). **This is the branch point:** from
here Chapters 3, 4, and 5 may be tackled in any order (see the campaign `FLOW`).

## Key NPCs

- **Mi Han** — caravan-master hired in Sian; the party's guide/logistician onward.
- **Langdon Warner** — the archaeologist whose plea launched the campaign; met at
  the caves. (Stat block with the Ch2 cast / `.actor`.)
- **The lama** — the strange holy man who reveals the stakes and sets the
  gathering quest; the pivotal NPC of the middle chapters.
- **Wang Yuanlu / Sir Marc Aurel Stein** — the caretaker priest and the famed
  (historical) archaeologist, framing the Library Cave's plundered history.
- **The Tokabhaya** — still surveilling, still sending visions.

## Clues & handouts (as information)

- **Warner's telegram** (*Decaying Splendor 3*) — the urgent, terse plea that
  drew the party to Tun-huang.
- **Gates 1 / Gates 2** — cryptic prophecy-fragments (e.g. the "red god… fat
  merchant's camel… the poor to paradise" verse) foreshadowing the metaphysics.
- **Gates 3** — the lama's Shambhala/Agartha history: the campaign's core exposition.
- **Gates 5** — the lama's advice on where to go first, seeding the any-order middle.
- **Hiuen-Tsiang background** and the regional *What Your Investigator Knows*
  handouts (Sian & the Kansu Corridor; the Tarim Basin).

## Keeper guidance

- Play Sian and the caravan-hiring as the party taking ownership of the expedition.
- Time the lama's revelation for the caves, after the Warner business resolves —
  it recontextualises everything and opens the branching quest.
- Keep the Library Cave's looting history in view; it seeds the campaign's
  recurring tension between Western "preservation" and plunder.

## Transition

With the lama's quest accepted and his route advice in hand, the campaign opens
into the **Gathering** phase: Chapters 3 (*Song of the Lost and Forgotten*),
4 (*Old Bones*), and 5 (*Feast and Famine*), attempted in any order, before the
climax.
